		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2014"></a><br><code>sle2014/paper16</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Origin Tracking in Attribute Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/KevinWilliams.html">Kevin Williams</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_16">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_16</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It extends higher-order attribute grammars with origin tracking as part of the metalanguage machinery.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5g.html"><span class="tagL">T5G: Traceability</span></a><ul><li> Origin tracking provides traceability links from transformation outputs back to their inputs.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> It relates to tree transformation/rewriting by tracking how constructed trees correspond to source trees.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> It concerns the semantics of attribute evaluation that constructs new syntax trees.
</li></ul></li></ul>
